{#- VARIANT DETAIL (definition) — plain-terms prose body -#}
<section class="sec reveal" id="recon-how-to-definition" style="padding-top:24px;">
  <div class="ct read read--doc">
    <div class="eyebrow" style="margin-bottom:8px;">In plain terms</div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:18px;">What &ldquo;reconcile&rdquo; means, plainly.</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>To reconcile an account in QuickBooks is to match your records against an outside source of truth &mdash; the bank or credit-card statement &mdash; for one statement period, and confirm they agree to the penny. You take the statement, tell QuickBooks the period&rsquo;s ending balance and date, then go down the list checking off every transaction that also appears on the statement. As you check items, QuickBooks tracks a running <em>difference</em> between what the statement says cleared and what you&rsquo;ve marked cleared. When that difference is <code>$0.00</code>, the account is reconciled for the period and you finish.</p>
      <p>The procedure is essentially identical in QuickBooks Online and QuickBooks Desktop &mdash; same logic, slightly different screens. What reconciling is <em>not</em> is a search for a number to make it balance. If the difference won&rsquo;t reach zero, something real is off &mdash; a missing transaction, a duplicate, a wrong amount, or a beginning balance that never tied &mdash; and the answer is to find it, not to plug it. This page is the clean step-by-step. If you want the deeper explanations &mdash; what the Reconcile tool itself does, the definition of bank reconciliation, or what to do when the difference won&rsquo;t close &mdash; those live on the linked pages below.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

